'''Ogawa Izumi Suijin Shrine''' (おがわいずみすいじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Yukawa, {{ill|lt=Shimizu Town (Shizuoka Prefecture)|Q1203168|WD=Q1203168|lt=Shimizu Town|1=Shimizu, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Sunto District|Q1142259|WD=Q1142259|1=Suntō District, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|WD=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}. It is sometimes written as “O'''gawa''' Izumi Suijin Shrine.”<ref>[http://www.shizuoka-jinjacho.or.jp/shokai/jinja.php?id=4403125 Ogawa Izumi Suijin Shrine] – Shizuoka Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines</ref>

=== Overview ===
The shrine is located in the central area of Shimizu Town, on the eastern bank just before the {{ill|lt=Kakita River|Q6349486|WD=Q6349486|1=Kakita River}} joins the {{ill|lt=Kano River|Q6364188|WD=Q6364188|1=Kano River}}, opposite the ruins of {{ill|lt=Tokura Castle (Izu Province)|Q11496230|WD=Q11496230|lt=Tokura Castle|1=Tokura Castle}} and Honjōyama Park.

The date of founding is unknown, but it is identified with the namesake {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} known as '''Ogawa Izumi Shrine''' (おがわいずみじんじゃ), and it is listed in the '{{ill|lt=Izu Province Shinkaichō|Q17193087|WD=Q17193087|1=Izu Province Shinkaichō}}' as “Junior Fourth Rank Upper, Ogawa Izumi Myōjin,” making it an ancient shrine.<ref name="gen">[https://genbu.net/data/izu/izumi_title.htm Ogawa Izumi Suijin Shrine] – Genbushi</ref><ref name="engi">[http://engishiki.org/izu/bun/iz140211-01.html Ogawa Izumi Suijin Shrine] – Research on Engishiki Shrines</ref>

During the Edo period, it was enshrined as a {{ill|lt=Kumano Shrine|Q3200355|WD=Q3200355|1=Kumano shrine}}, and even after being renamed to its current name in the Meiji period, it has retained this character, such as by enshrining Kumano Fusumi no Mikoto, the deity of {{ill|lt=Kumano Nachi Taisha|Q710359|WD=Q710359|1=Kumano Nachi Taisha}}.<ref name="gen"/><ref name="engi"/>

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 8 ({{ill|lt=1875|Q7764|WD=Q7764|1=1875}}), it was designated as a village shrine.<ref name="engi"/>

